have worked to legitimize their practices through an overt embrace of evolving forms such as esotericism and supernaturalism.Taking a two-track approach, this book explores the complex dynamics of the construction of the modern self and its relation to the modern preoccupation with magic. Essays examine how modern “rational” consciousness is generated and maintained and how proponents of both magical and scientific traditions rationalize evidence to fit accepted orthodoxy. This book also describes how people unsatisfied with the norms of modern subjectivity embrace various forms of magic—and the methods these modern practitioners use to legitimate magic in the modern world.A compelling assessment of magic from the early modern period to today, Magic in the Modern World shows how, despite the dominant culture’s emphatic denial of their validity, older forms of magic persist and develop while new forms of magic continue to emerge.In addition to the editors, contributors include Egil Asprem, Erik Davis, Megan Goodwin, Dan Harms, Adam Jortner, and Benedek Láng.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aMagicxHistory. 0aMagic. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aWiccan.  adisenchantment.  alegitimization.  amodernity.  asupernatural.  asuperstition.  atwentieth century.  awitchcraft.1 aAsprem, Egil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBever, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBever, Edward, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarms, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJortner, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g